testsuite.system-out:
Calculate the number of carbon atoms that are in a $2.0$-carat diamond that weighs $0.4000$g.
\newcommand{\scientific}[1]{\num[round-precision=4,round-mode=figures,scientific-notation=true]{#1}}
The molar mass of carbon is $12.01$g mol$^{-1}$.\\
The number of moles $=$ mass $\div$ molar mass $=\dfrac{0.40}{12.0}=0.0333$ moles.\\
Therefore the number of molecules $=$ moles $\times$ Avogadro's number 
$=0.0333\times(\scientific{6.0220e+23})
=\scientific{2.0057e+22}$ molecules.
\newcommand{\scientific}[1]{\num[round-precision=4,round-mode=figures,scientific-notation=true]{#1}}
\scientific{2.0057e+22}
